	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65311001"><p>
Making it harder / more expensive for regular people to file their taxes electronically, while cutting the staff processing returns, especially paper returns, and cutting knowledgeable staff who audit returns, especially the more complex returns of wealthy people is really going to save the government money.<nobr> <wbr></nobr>/s
</p><p>
I guess it will save some people money, just not regular people<nobr> <wbr></nobr>...
</p><p>
<a href="https://thehill.com/opinion/white-house/5248491-irs-doge-taxpayer-impacts/" title="thehill.com">DOGE&rsquo;s IRS cuts will cost the average American a fortune</a> [thehill.com] </p><p><div class="quote"><p>Roughly 70 percent of the personnel cuts thus far have been in enforcement, which will make it easier to avoid detection for the <b>millionaire and billionaire tax cheats who evade an estimated $150 billion in taxes every year.</b> It is estimated that every dollar cut from enforcement costs five to nine dollars in revenue. <b>So if Musk tries to cut $10 billion from IRS enforcement spending, he will be risking $50-90 billion in lost revenue each year.</b> That&rsquo;s a strange strategy for someone who claims he wants to make the government more cost-efficient.
</p><p>
<b>The Inflation Reduction Act&rsquo;s restored funding for the IRS yielded successes. As of last summer, the agency had collected over $1 billion just from 1,600 millionaires who owed but had failed to pay at least $250,000 each. It also informed Microsoft that it owed $29 billion in back taxes</b> and had plans to increase audits on big companies (those worth more than $250 million), large partnerships (those with over $10 million in assets) and individuals with income over $10 million.</p></div></div>
	</div>

